1. c4 c5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 0-0 8. 0-0 
d6 {This pawn sacrifice has been known for many years and was employed by many great 
players such as Tal or Tseshkovsky, just to mention two of them.} 9. Nxc6 {I believe, 
only this move is really challenging.} bxc6 10. Bxc6 Rb8 { This is definitely the 
best choice - Black puts the pressure on the Pb2 and makes it tougher to develop 
the queen's bishop.} ({White's task is much easier after}10... Bh3 $6 11. Bxa8 Qxa8 
12. f3 Bxf1 13. Kxf1 Rc8 (13... Ng4 14. Qd5 $16 ) 14. Qd3 Qc6 15. Be3 {leaves Black 
with no compensation at all. In fact, all 10 games were won by White here!} ) 11. 
Bg2 {Obviously, the bishop was vulnerable in Black's camp, so it is coming home.} 
Qa5 {This is the only adequate way of maintaining the tension. Now, when b2-b3 is 
impossible the attack on the c4-pawn is going to be quite effective. 0-1 (29) Rubene,I 
(2330) -Solomunovic,I Tuzla 1991} ({Bad is}11... Be6 $2 12. b3 Ne4 13. Bxe4 Bxc3 
14. Bh6 {Black was busted in Sundararajan,K - Kaidanov,G Douglas 2018} ) 12. Qc2 
{An important consolidating move. The queen covers both the b2-pawn and the c3-knight.} 
Bf5 ({Somehow,}12... Be6 $6 {is Black's first choice in practice, but this seems 
inferior:} 13. Bd2 Qh5 ({After}13... Bxc4 14. Nd5 Qb5 15. Nxe7+ Kh8 16. Nc6 Bxe2 
17. Nxb8 Bxf1 18. Rxf1 Rxb8 19. b3 {White got the decisive advantage in Stohl, I 
- Enders, P Germany 1997} ) ({I also examined}13... Qc5 $146 14. b3 d5 15. Be3 d4 
16. Na4 Qh5 17. Bxd4 Ng4 18. h3 Bxd4 19. hxg4 Bxg4 20. Rad1 $16 ) 14. b3 Rfc8 {took 
place in many games. I am quite surprised that nobody has played here} 15. Rad1 
$146 {The next few moves are almost forced:} d5 16. Bf4 Rb6 17. Bf3 Qh3 18. Rxd5 
Nxd5 19. Nxd5 Bxd5 20. Bxd5 {White's passers are supported by the powerful bishops, 
and Black can hardly withstand that.} ) (12... Bb7 {was seen in Ribli, Z - Powierski, 
E Germany 2018. Now my new natural idea is} 13. Rb1 $146 $5 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Rfc8 15. 
b3 d5 {This is the only attempt to take advantage of the temporary activity.} 16. 
Bd2 $1 {Correctly letting Black regain the pawn.} dxc4 17. bxc4 Rxb1 18. Rxb1 Rxc4 
19. Rb8+ {A very annoying check.} Bf8 20. Qd3 Qc7 21. Qd8 Qxd8 22. Rxd8 $14 {White 
has a long-lasting advantage due to the active rook.} ) 13. Qd2 ({Much more common 
is}13. e4 {, but after} Be6 14. b3 Nxe4 {the complications turn out favorable for 
Black:} 15. Nxe4 Bxa1 16. Bg5 Bf5 17. Bxe7 Rfe8 18. Bxd6 Rbd8 19. Rxa1 Rxd6 $15 
{Grachev,B - Khalifman,A Tyumen 2012} ) Be6 ({In case of}13... Qb4 $6 14. b3 Nd7 
$2 15. Nd5 {Black's position collapses at once.} ) ({Dubious is also}13... Ng4 $6 
14. Nd5 Qxd2 15. Nxe7+ Kh8 16. Bxd2 $16 ) ({Pointless is}13... Rfc8 $6 {Silseth,S-Wegner,H 
Gausdal 1991 as after} 14. b3 Rxb3 $2 15. Nd5 $18 { Black cannot avoid a massive 
loss of material.} ) 14. b3 Rxb3 {Black manages to take the pawn back. but his queen 
is going to be stuck in the corner for a while.} 15. axb3 Qxa1 16. Nb5 $1 { The 
knight is heading to c6 in order to restrict the mobility of Black's pieces.} a6 
17. Na7 Qb1 (17... Nd7 18. Nc6 Re8 {took place in Efimenko,Z - Melkumyan,H Warsaw 
2016 At this moment I mostly like} 19. Qc2 $146 $1 {In the endgame that arises after} 
Qc3 20. Qxc3 Bxc3 21. Bg5 Kf8 22. Rc1 $14 {Black suffers from the strong pressure 
on the Pe7.} ) 18. Qb4 $1 Qa2 19. Nc6 Re8 20. Bd2 $146 $5 {This natural developing 
move is a novelty.} ({Less promising is}20. e4 Nd7 21. Bg5 {Meier,G - Kovalev, V 
Baku 2016 Now Black should have played} h6 $146 $1 22. Bxe7 Ne5 23. Nxe5 Bxe5 24. 
Bxd6 Bxd6 25. Qxd6 Qxb3 26. c5 a5 {the strong a-passer yields Black a sufficient 
counter-play.} ) Nd7 ({The plan of liquidating the Nc6 does not guarantee Black 
equality:}20... Bd7 21. h3 Bxc6 22. Bxc6 Rf8 23. Be3 Qxe2 24. Qb7 $36 {The strong 
bishops put Black in a difficult situation, even though he is a pawn up.} ) 21. 
Bg5 Nf6 ({After}21... h6 22. Bxe7 Nc5 23. Bxd6 Nxb3 24. c5 Qxe2 25. Re1 $14 {the 
c5-pawn overwhelms Black's a-passer.} ) 22. Re1 h6 23. Be3 Bd7 24. h3 $14 {The presence 
