1. c4 c5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 {This is a common choice for Grunfeld players. Black 
aims to set up a reversed Maroczy pawn structure whilst preventing White from executing 
the d2-d4 break.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Nxc3 {Among Black's minor options, this looks 
like the most attractive - Black goes for the active development, a-la Grunfeld. 
The drawback is clear: it yields White more control of the centre and opens the 
b-file, so the b7-pawn is now under pressure.} (5... e6 {This was played by many 
strong players, including Vladimir Kramnik.} 6. Nxd5 exd5 7. Qb3 $1 Nc6 (7... c4 
8. Qb5+ Nc6 9. Bxd5 $16 ) 8. Qxd5 Bd6 {It definitely makes sense to keep the queens 
on the board.} ({After}8... Qxd5 $6 9. Bxd5 Nb4 10. Be4 f5 11. Bb1 $16 {White was 
just a pawn up in Gelfand, B - Kramnik, V Sanghi Nagar 1994} ) 9. Nf3 0-0 10. 0-0 
Be6 {Natural play from both sides led to this position in Jussupow, A - Zaichik, 
G Vilnius 1978 In my opinion, White should have continued} 11. Qd3 $146 Be7 12. 
Qc2 Nb4 13. Qb1 $14 {The activity of Black's pieces is practically neutralized, 
while White has a healthy extra pawn.} ) (5... Nb6 {is similar to 5...Nc7. Black 
is interested in retaining the current pawn structure, so he retreats the knight 
in order to play ...e7-e5.} 6. d3 e5 (6... Nc6 7. Be3 e5 {, as in Malakhatko,V - 
Borisenko,V Lvov 2016 can be well met by} 8. Rc1 $146 Be6 (8... Be7 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 
{transposes to 6...e5} ) 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Nf3 f6 11. 0-0 $14 {The vulnerability 
of the doubled pawns outweighs Black's strong light-squared bishop.} ) 7. Be3 Be7 
8. Rc1 Nc6 ({In case of}8... 0-0 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. 0-0 Be6 (10... Bf5 {, as in Velicka,P 
- Babula,V Havlickuv Brod 2008 can also be met by} 11. Ne4 $1 {, and then} c4 12. 
Nc5 Nd5 13. Rxc4 b5 14. Rc1 Nxe3 15. fxe3 Rc8 16. a3 $14 {leaves Black with no real 
compensation for the pawn.} ) 11. Ne4 $1 { The knight reached c5 and provides White 
with a definite initiative on the queenside. For instance,} c4 12. Nc5 Bxc5 13. 
Bxc5 Re8 14. dxc4 Nxc4 15. b3 $14 ) 9. Bxc6+ (9. Nf3 $5 {is another interesting 
option.} ) bxc6 10. Nf3 f6 11. Ne4 c4 {A sad necessity.} 12. dxc4 Qxd1+ 13. Kxd1 
Be6 14. Nfd2 $14 {White's king is safe, so Black does not have sufficient compensation.} 
) (5... Nf6 {This retreat is rarely seen on the high level.} 6. d3 e5 {The most 
consistent.} (6... Nc6 $6 {, as took place in a couple of games traditionally runs 
into} 7. Bxc6+ $146 bxc6 8. Qa4 Qb6 9. Nf3 Bh3 10. Ng5 Bf5 11. Be3 $16 {with massive 
pressure on the weak c-pawns.} ) 7. Bg5 Be7 8. Qb3 Nc6 ({Hardly better is}8... Qd7 
9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Rc1 0-0 11. Ne4 $14 ) 9. Bxc6+ {A well-timed exchange.} bxc6 10. 
Nf3 Qc7 11. 0-0 0-0 12. Qc2 $14 {As usual, the c-pawns are very weak.} ) (5... Nb4 
6. Nf3 N8c6 {The most natural.} (6... N4c6 7. 0-0 e5 {was seen in a couple of games. 
In my opinion, White should underline the drawbacks of Black's artificial setup 
by means of} 8. Qa4 $146 $1 Bd7 (8... Nd7 {is well met by} 9. Nh4 $1 Nb6 10. Bxc6+ 
bxc6 11. Qxc6+ Bd7 12. Qe4 $16 ) 9. Qb3 Na5 10. Qd1 {It turns out that the deep 
point behind the queen moves was to invite Black's bishop to d7 where it locks the 
d-file and thus makes it possible for White to push d3-d4.} Nbc6 ({Ineffective is}10... 
Nac6 11. e3 Bg4 12. h3 Be6 13. d4 cxd4 14. exd4 exd4 15. Ne2 Bc5 16. Nf4 $16 ) 11. 
e3 $1 Be6 ({Or}11... Bg4 12. h3 Bh5 13. Qa4 Bd6 14. d4 $36 ) 12. d4 cxd4 13. exd4 
exd4 14. Nb5 $14 {White regains the pawn under favourable circumstance as Black's 
setup lacks harmony.} ) 7. a3 Na6 8. d3 e5 { Black manages to temporarily take control 
over the centre, but the lack of developments starts to tell now.} 9. Nd2 Be7 10. 
Nc4 { A perfect square for the knight where it attacks the e5-pawn and cannot be 
chased by Black.} f6 11. f4 $1 {A well-timed break.} exf4 12. Bxf4 0-0 13. 0-0 Nd4 
14. Nd5 {White was better in Ragozin,E - Eljanov,V Alushta 2000} ) 6. dxc3 $5 {With 
this recapture White aims to reach a comfortable endgame with a slight edge.} (6. 
bxc3 {is by far most common, but} Nc6 7. Nf3 e5 8. 0-0 Be7 {seems perfectly playable 
for Black. There is an example from my own practice:} 9. d3 0-0 10. Rb1 Qe8 11. 
Nd2 Rb8 12. a4 Be6 13. Nc4 b6 {Black had nothing to worry about in Gelfand, B - 
Roiz, M St Petersburg 2018} ) Qxd1+ ({Hardly more attractive is}6... Qc7 7. Nf3 
Nc6 8. Be3 e6 9. 0-0 Be7 10. Qc2 0-0 11. Ng5 $14 {Black struggled to develop his 
Bc8 in Novak, K - Jelica, M Sibenik 2010} ) 7. Kxd1 Nc6 (7... e5 8. e4 Nc6 9. Kc2 
{leads to the same.} ) 8. Kc2 e5 {This advance keeps the Bc8 unlocked, but also 
weakens d5.} ({I also tested}8... Bd7 $146 9. e4 0-0-0 10. Be3 b6 11. Nf3 e5 (11... 
g6 12. Ng5 Be8 13. f4 Bg7 14. e5 {offers White a small, but long-lasting space advantage.} 
) 12. h4 $1 {An interesting concept: White will either grab some more space or provoke 
the weakening h7-h5.} Be7 (12... h5 13. Ng5 $14 ) 13. h5 Kc7 14. Bh3 $14 ) 9. e4 
{White locks the long diagonal in order to fix the favourable pawn structure and 
plans to swap the light-squared bishops soon.} (9. Bd5 Ne7 {leads nowhere.} ) Be7 
(9... Be6 {led to a similar scenario:} 10. Be3 Be7 11. Bh3 $14 {Moreno Sanchis, 
J - Pablo Marin, A Spain 2004} ) 10. Be3 $146 {The most flexible move. It makes 
sense to keep the knight on its initial square for a while.} ({Less precise is}10. 
Nf3 Be6 11. Be3 f6 {Zaltsman, V-Benjamin, J New York 1977} ) 0-0 11. Bh3 $1 {This 
is the only way of claiming superiority.} Rd8 (11... b5 12. Rd1 b4 13. Rd5 $14 ) 
12. Rd1 Rxd1 13. Kxd1 Bxh3 14. Nxh3 {The knight wouldn't be stuck there for too 
long.} Rd8+ 15. Kc2 f6 16. Ng1 Kf7 17. Nf3 $14 {White has the superior bishop.} 
